```

Default I2C address 0x40; A0/A1 select 0x40-0x4F. The chip auto-zeros; no calibration ritual needed for hobby use.

```cpp
#include <OneWire.h>
#include <DallasTemperature.h>

const int ONE_WIRE_PIN = 4;
OneWire bus(ONE_WIRE_PIN);
DallasTemperature dt(&bus);
DeviceAddress addr;

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  dt.begin();
  Serial.print("count: ");
  Serial.println(dt.getDeviceCount());
}

void loop() {
  dt.requestTemperatures();
  for (uint8_t i = 0; i < dt.getDeviceCount(); i++) {
    if (dt.getAddress(addr, i)) {
      Serial.print("dev ");
      for (uint8_t b = 0; b < 8; b++) {
        if (addr[b] < 16) Serial.print('0');
        Serial.print(addr[b], HEX);
      }
      Serial.print(" T=");
      Serial.println(dt.getTempC(addr), 2);
    }
  }
  delay(1000);
}
```

Wire: 4.7 k pull-up from DATA to VCC. Each DS18B20 has a unique 64-bit address printed on the body; addresses are stable so you can hardcode them after first enumeration to lock sensor identity to physical position.

```cpp
const int TRIG = 9;
const int ECHO = 10;
const unsigned long TIMEOUT_US = 30000;  // 30 ms = ~5 m

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  pinMode(TRIG, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(ECHO, INPUT);
}

float distanceCm() {
  digitalWrite(TRIG, LOW);
  delayMicroseconds(2);
  digitalWrite(TRIG, HIGH);
  delayMicroseconds(10);
  digitalWrite(TRIG, LOW);
  unsigned long us = pulseIn(ECHO, HIGH, TIMEOUT_US);
  if (us == 0) return -1.0;
  return us * 0.01715f;  // (us * 343 m/s) / (2 * 100 us/cm)
}

void loop() {
  float d = distanceCm();
  if (d < 0) Serial.println("timeout");
  else Serial.println(d, 1);
  delay(100);
}
```

Pitfall: the HC-SR04 needs 5 V on VCC and TRIG, but its ECHO is also 5 V. On a 3.3 V MCU, divide ECHO with 1k + 2k or use a 5 V tolerant pin. Don't run two sonars in parallel without time-slicing; their bursts collide.

4-wire load cell wiring: E+ -> red (excitation +), E- -> black, A+ -> green (signal +), A- -> white. HX711 board exposes those terminals.

```cpp
#include "HX711.h"
const int DOUT = 4;
const int SCK = 5;
HX711 scale;

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  scale.begin(DOUT, SCK);
  // Tare zero with no load
  scale.tare();
  // Calibration scale: place a known weight (e.g. 1 kg) and capture the raw delta
  // scale.set_scale(420.0);  // calibration constant from a one-time bench cal
}

void loop() {
  if (scale.is_ready()) {
    float grams = scale.get_units(10);  // average of 10 reads
    Serial.println(grams, 1);
  }
  delay(200);
}
```

Calibration constant: place a known weight, read raw, divide raw by weight in grams to get the constant; pass to set_scale(). For drift, retare every time the system powers up. The HX711 is internally noisy; mount it away from EMI, decouple with 100 nF + 10 uF, and run shielded twisted pair from cell to board.

Raw mag readings live on a sphere centered at the origin in a perfect world. In reality the sphere is offset (hard-iron, from nearby magnetic materials on the PCB) and squashed into an ellipsoid (soft-iron, from ferromagnetic distortion).

Calibration procedure:
1. Rotate the device through every orientation for 30-60 seconds while logging raw x, y, z.
2. Hard-iron: bx = (max(x) + min(x)) / 2, similarly by, bz. Subtract from readings.
3. Soft-iron (simple): scale_x = (max(x) - min(x)) / 2, similarly y, z; divide each axis by its scale to renormalize to a unit sphere.

```cpp
float mx = (raw_x - bx) / sx;
float my = (raw_y - by) / sy;
float mz = (raw_z - bz) / sz;
float heading_deg = atan2(my, mx) * 180.0 / PI;
if (heading_deg < 0) heading_deg += 360.0;
```

For the proper soft-iron correction (3x3 matrix), use the MotionCal tool or a least-squares ellipsoid fit. Keep the magnetometer 1+ cm from any speaker, motor, or current-carrying trace.

```cpp
#include <SparkFun_APDS9960.h>
SparkFun_APDS9960 apds;

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  apds.init();
  apds.enableGestureSensor(true);
}

void loop() {
  if (apds.isGestureAvailable()) {
    switch (apds.readGesture()) {
      case DIR_UP:    Serial.println("up");    break;
      case DIR_DOWN:  Serial.println("down");  break;
      case DIR_LEFT:  Serial.println("left");  break;
      case DIR_RIGHT: Serial.println("right"); break;
      case DIR_NEAR:  Serial.println("near");  break;
      case DIR_FAR:   Serial.println("far");   break;
    }
  }
}
```

I2C 0x39, 3.3 V, INT pin to a GPIO if you want interrupt-driven detection. The chip also does color (RGB) and proximity. Gestures need a hand 5-15 cm from the lens; sunlight saturates it.

```cpp
#include <Adafruit_VEML6075.h>
Adafruit_VEML6075 uv;

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  uv.begin();
  uv.setIntegrationTime(VEML6075_100MS);
  uv.setHighDynamic(true);
}

void loop() {
  Serial.print("UVA "); Serial.print(uv.readUVA());
  Serial.print(" UVB "); Serial.print(uv.readUVB());
  Serial.print(" UVI "); Serial.println(uv.readUVI());
  delay(1000);
}
```

I2C 0x10. UV index is 0-11+ with 11+ being extreme. Cover the package with a UV-transparent window (PMMA / acrylic, NOT polycarbonate which absorbs UVB). Indoor readings are essentially zero; expect index 6-9 at noon on a clear day.

```cpp
#include <SensirionI2CScd4x.h>
SensirionI2CScd4x scd4x;

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  Wire.begin();
  scd4x.begin(Wire);
  scd4x.stopPeriodicMeasurement();
  scd4x.startPeriodicMeasurement();
}

void loop() {
  uint16_t co2 = 0; float t = 0; float h = 0;
  bool ready = false;
  scd4x.getDataReadyFlag(ready);
  if (ready) {
    if (scd4x.readMeasurement(co2, t, h) == 0) {
      Serial.print("CO2 "); Serial.print(co2);
      Serial.print(" ppm  T "); Serial.print(t, 1);
      Serial.print(" RH "); Serial.println(h, 1);
    }
  }
  delay(5000);
}
```

I2C 0x62. NDIR optical, real CO2 not eCO2. 5 sec sample period, 175 mA peak during measurement. For battery use the single-shot mode: `measureSingleShot()` then sleep for a minute. ASC (automatic self-calibration) requires fresh outdoor air weekly to anchor; if your device lives in a sealed room, disable ASC and force-calibrate with a known reference.
